The first virtual provider comes to the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile phone market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, the Czech suppliers offer virtually all services, as they are also offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classics at lower prices.
Maybe this one won't be waiting for a long time.
We have often reported on Mobil.cz that Czech mobile operators are working among the most expensive in Europe.
This also confirmed the telecommunication authority ČTă, which drew attention to the fact that the price of SMS is higher here than in the rest of the European Union.
According to the European Commission's final steps in the regulation of roaming fees, a paradoxical situation is likely to arise - for some customers of Czech mobile communications providers, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, it lacks the competition that really makes a combat message.
Perhaps it sounds paradoxical, but there are three mobile networks in the Czech Republic and a penetration of well over 100 %.
On the other hand, mobile operators like to skim over the fact that there is extremely much competition in the Czech market.
The President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority, Pavel Dvořák, has often said that there is no room for another supplier in the Czech Republic in the past.
It is probably true that a classic provider with its own network no longer has a lot of opportunities (it would probably not find any frequencies at all).
There is, however, another possibility - a virtual provider.
Especially the entry of virtual providers into the mobile phone market brought a clear price reduction, to which the classic mobile phone providers had to respond.
Before the entry of such companies as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile, there were similar voices on the UK market as in the Czech Republic.
However, it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can be truly successful.
By the way, you don't need to look for examples for a long time.
In February this we reported on the launch of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider managed to win more than 100 thousand customers and thus become the five largest supplier in the country.
Behind Mobilking is the Penta financial group, which has U:fon in the Czech Republic, among others.
The advantage of virtual providers is that one can focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order to function effectively, virtual providers need far less customers than a classic provider.
They do not need relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers usually profile themselves as low-cost firms - they offer cheap phone calls and SMS, which is often accompanied by a less extensive service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a pretty good move to put on a non-cliché-like target group.
This provider is aimed specifically at men.
“Real guys choose Mobilking - the provider they like and whom they can trust,” said David Seibert, CEO of the Mobile Entertainment Company, the operating firm of this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a concept similar to that in Poland could be found in the Czech Republic.
Vodafone Miroslav Čepický's press speaker also doubts: \"The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment based on most virtual suppliers.
In addition, it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the offer of services,
