Maybe better times are coming.
Non-official information indicates that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
Until now, however, this is surrounded by an invincible wall of silence.
“At this moment we do not assume that there is room in the Czech Republic for a full-scale virtual provider.
The Czech market has great specificities over other markets.
So far we have not yet addressed a subject with a complex and serious project in this field - says in his statement for Mobil.cz Vlastimil Sršeň from the press department of Telefónica O2.
Other suppliers also point to the specifics of the Czech market.
The press spokesperson of T-Mobile Martina Kemrová adds in rare agreement with the O2 statement: “We haven’t yet found a viable and both-sidedly beneficial project that could be further built on,
And she adds: “The T-Mobile network will hardly open up a virtual provider until the end of the year.
At this moment, we must already have a specific offer to be able to think in the short term,
Vodafone focuses more on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický says: “We are open to negotiations with potential virtual providers, especially in the area of sharing costs and infrastructure.
We consider this from the point of view of our customers as the best.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to search for a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile Internet,
The responsible authorities - with the suppliers hand in hand
It is easy to understand how mobile telephone providers operate, another provider was called more competition, this would result in lower prices and thus also a decrease in profits.
Why, then, should market entry be facilitated by such a competitor?
The fact that providers can draw on a strand when it comes to something also demonstrates the long up and down of U:fon.
The probably strongest pressure towards ČTÜ was at the time U:fon entered the market, from the company T-Mobile.
