Discussion on bilingual education: education in English-speaking environments
In this issue of Education Watch, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi discuss the positions of candidates for bilingual training.
Lance T. Izumi, senior academic assistant in California Studies and senior director in the Department of Education at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is a co-author of the book \"Not as good as you think: Why the middle class needs a choice of schools,
Addressing Hispanic voters is a complicated task.
Barrack Obama's proposals on education are a typical example of this.
Obama’s election campaign mentions that “the probability of African-American and Hispanic students successfully completing school is lower than in white students - what’s right.
In order to close this gap in performance, Obama's education plan recommends a bilingual transition phase in training for those who first learn English.
However, the question to Obama is whether his use of bilingual education, which places the emphasis on teaching in languages other than English, contradicts his interest in reducing the distance from school.
As an example, let's take \"Sixth Street Prep\" a primary school in eastern Los Angeles.
The majority of pupils are Hispanic and come from low-income families.
More than one third of the students, many of whom are only recently in the country, learn English.
Nevertheless, in 2008, amazing 100 percent of fourth grade students passed the state examination in math at a good level.
Also surprisingly, 93 percent of children from the fourth year of school were well rated in the English examination.
This amazing success has been achieved with methods other than those preferred by Obama.
School Sixth Street focuses on review and exercise, on continuous control of knowledge and an attitude that tolerates no exceptions.
