Negotiation - From the blood that became safe again
Hema-Quebec celebrated the 10th anniversary of her founding yesterday, and her president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to rejoice because Hema-Quebec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood banks in the world.
And, above all, she regained the public's confidence, which had been severely shaken by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As we know, the national blood reserves administered by the blood donation service of the Canadian Red Cross were contaminated during the 1980s with the HI virus and the hepatitis C virus.
In the light of this drama and public dissatisfaction, in February 1994, the Government of Canada launched a public investigation, led by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy and to draw up guidelines to prevent a further disaster of this kind.
While Judge Krever was still reluctant to submit his report, at that time several provinces placed a committee on the legs, whose goal was to develop a new system for the administration of blood vessels in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this mission.
According to the reports of Gélineau and Krever, two blood banks were established in Canada: Hema-Quebec, which is responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian blood company to provide the other provinces and the two territories.
`1998, when Hema-Quebec took up her work, hardly 38% of the people had confidence in the blood conservation system in Quebec, Dr. Décary recalls.
The situation was discouraging.
Because of the enormous efforts made to improve the safety of the blood vessels and by working in this area during the following years, we have regained the confidence of the public,' she says, before she proudly stressed that almost 94% of the population of Quebec now had confidence in Hema-Quebec at the beginning of 2008.
Dr. Décary, however, retains in the consciousness that 'trust is something extremely fragile'.
Since its establishment on 28 September 1998, Hema-Quebec has acted on the principle of caution.
At this time we experienced the occurrence of numerous cases of the human form of cattle madness in Europe, a new type of Creutzfeldt-Jacob disease, this woman, who has been in charge since its founding in 1998.
`And we did not have the slightest idea of whether this disease could be transmitted over the blood.
So we called on one of the main guidelines of the Krever and Gélineau reports, which are said to be exclusive measures, if one does not know and if a disease only progresses slowly, as is obviously the case with Creutzfeldt-Jacob disease, which is expressed by a degeneration of the brain, which inevitably leads to death.
So in April 1999, there was no blood of people who had remained in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago, without any doubt, this disease has been proven to be transmitted over the blood.
So this event has shown us that the principle of caution we applied has a sense of purpose.
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for detecting HIV appeared on the market: the nucleic acid (NST) tests, which allow the presence of the virus itself directly in the donor's blood, and not that of the antibody against the virus, as was the case with the previous tests.
The NST allowed to shorten the incubation time between the time when the person was infected and that when the first viruses can be detected by our techniques in the blood, the specialist explains.
This time could be reduced to a duration of less than a week.
Thus, the risk that some donors could be infected without knowing it, and one could not recognize it, was significantly reduced.
These improvements allowed a significant reduction in the risk of transmission of AIDS via a blood transfusion.
Nowadays, one of 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV infected blood.
'In other words, this means that 12 million blood cans would have to be distributed before someone gets infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood cells each year, it would take more than 24 years before a case of transmission of HIV via a blood vessel.
I believe that you can feel comfortable nowadays when you get a blood transfusion or write down to restore your health', says Hema-Quebec's management chief.
`Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen can get into the system.
Only last year did the Chikungunya virus appear on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by insects over the blood.
We need to monitor uninterrupted', Dr Décary continues before she emphasizes that Hema-Quebec, in addition to a safe supply, must also provide sufficient supplies.
'The need increases because the population ages.
As anticancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also affects the blood donors network, with an average of only 3% of Quebec's blood donors.
Every healthy person who is 18 years of age or older and meets the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, that is, six times a year.
On average, 14% of those who provide their blood are not accepted because of AIDS or malaria, for example, and those who have traveled to a country where malaria has been spread for one year are excluded from blood donation.
This 3% enables us to obtain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Lack of supplies are very rare.
But it is necessary to renew the members of this donor network when they get older and can no longer donate blood.
It is hard to convince people to donate blood, but especially to keep it and to make it become regular donors.
Life is so hectic today that you rarely find time to spend an hour on blood donation', regrets Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Quebec not only supplies blood, but also human tissues, including bone transplants, heartbeats, eyeballs and skin, which are used almost exclusively in severe burns.
These tissues are examined, processed and frozen before they are stored in Hema-Quebec, which also manages the only Quebec Public Fountain Blood Bank.
In the umbilical cord, previously considered as biomedical waste, there is rich blood in stem cells that can serve to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
'A few weeks ago we celebrated the insertion of our thousandth umbilical cord blood sample, and we plan to decrease more than a thousand annually.
'We should probably start making it available for transplants at the beginning of next year', explains Dr Décary, who describes this program of umbilical cord blood loss as very popular.
'Many mothers are convinced not to have access to it' because Hema-Quebec lacks the means to offer this complex and costly program in all Quebec hospitals.
