The psychology of overbiding - or why we are willing to pay more
In case of auctions, buyers tend to spend more and thus overvalue the bid.
Neurologists and economic researchers at the University of New York have now succeeded in discovering the neurological-economic foundations of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to a study published in the Science magazine, people in a competition, such as an auction on eBay, do not want to give up and are therefore willing to pay even higher prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this “game” with experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers should play Lotto while the other participated in a playful action - in both cases the active brain regions of the subjects were examined using functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
In both games the participants were able to win money, but an increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the brain, was measured in the case of losers of the auction, in which the overriding of the opponent plays a major role.
In addition to many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the “self reward” of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore said that the increase in prices was explained by the avoidance of an overreaction of the striatum.
In order to substantiate their thesis, economists in the research group have also conducted studies to track the money.
In this case, three groups should compete against one partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the true value of the product, after which they made their efforts.
Another group was also promised $15 reward, in case they come out of the game as winners.
The third group received 15 dollars before the auction, which was also lost in the event of a lost game.
The difference between the two groups was that the emphasis on one was on winning while the other was on losing.
However, as evidence of the hypothesis expressed by neurologists, the members of the “non-lost” group were ready for higher stakes than those in the control or profit group.
\"These results cannot be deduced from any previous economic theory.
In fact, the practices observed in auctions have so far been justified only with the joy of winning, or of avoiding risk.
The contradiction between these two theories was resolved thanks to the pictorial neurological process, so that we have now prepared a third explanation - said Andrew Schotter, professor of the Faculty of Economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should the doctor visit?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among leading causes of death.
The number of infected people is estimated to be one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand are treated, which is that patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for liver diseases caused by various viruses.
Symptoms are often similar - liver inflammation and jaundice are common, but the pathogens and diseases differ.
Depending on the pathogen, hepatitis viruses spread in two different ways: for hepatitis A and E, by the digestive tract (for example by contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted through blood and other bodily fluids (such as sperm, mucous membrane or saliva).
Travelers are advised against viruses A and B at any time, against virus C there is no vaccine.
Symptoms in hepatitis A occur about two-three weeks after consumption of contaminated food and are generally accompanied by discomfort, weakness, abdominal pain and vomiting.
After that, yellow growth occurs on the skin and in the eyes, the stool becomes bright, the urine dark, and the healing can last up to two-three weeks.
Worldwide, about 1 million people die each year from hepatitis B, far more serious diseases such as liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that estimates suggest that only every tenth infected person is in medication treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: untreated can lead to liver cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, as the pathogen secretly destroys the liver cells - in many cases the first symptoms after 20-30 years show up.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular checks, is essential.
There are three groups in which this disease is more common: those who had undergone blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattoos.
Currently, the number of chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide is estimated to be 200 million.
As the disease is already detectable in a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult the home doctor for the first signs of unknown origin.
It is recognized in due time that the disease can be cured, the virus can be eradicated, thus banning the risk of infection and preventing the emergence of cancer.
The 30th of September is the World Day of Hepatitis, organised for the first time by patient representatives worldwide in 2004.
The aim of the action is to strengthen awareness of this chronic liver inflammation caused by viruses, their origin and the importance of early detection.
