Intelligent car imitates Hummel's flight
What would be the best method of developing new technologies to prevent accidents if not imitate the obstacle sensors from nature?
For example, those of bees.
At the CEATEC in Japan, an amazing project was presented in which the Nissan engineers were inspired by Hummeln in creating new accident avoiding systems.
In cooperation with Tokyo University, Nissan has built a BR23C biomimetic system controlled by autobots, a mini-car equipped with the properties of bees, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that avoids any collisions.
In flight, each bee forms its own oval, private area, which is very similar to our own protective shield, said Kazuhhiro Doi, product manager for technology PR and research development, at the exhibition.
The composite eye of the bee, which can see in any direction and at an angle of over 300 degrees, plays an important role.
In order to imitate the function of the compound eye, the researchers took up the idea of the laser-controlled distance gauge.
This identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C in a 180-degree face within 2 metres, calculates their distances and sends signals to the microprocessor on board, which immediately initiates the collision avoidance process.
The obstacle is recorded in second-break parts, and the auto robot immediately changes the course, similar to the movement of bees by rotating the tires around the corresponding angle.
In contrast to previous systems, this maneuver takes place instinctively.
\"If it were not, the auto robot could not react quickly enough to avoid the obstacles, explained Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the Autoroboter project.
The system must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the innermost and most vulnerable part of the shield - a layer within which accidents are still considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect the behaviour of bees if they deviate from other bees.
And this needs to be done in the fraction of a second.
However, the deviation, unlike bees, cannot be up, down, or even diagonally - it can only be two-dimensional, only in the direction of the practicability of the tyres.
While bees have an infinite range of options for eviction from other bees, the researchers at the autorobot were able to use only the rotational movement, or acceleration and braking.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and more energy efficient and therefore have a longer life than conventional lithium ion batteries.
Andoh explained that it comes to the instinctive, intelligent response, and less to the processing of the data, and even less to the ability to store it.
This device has to process only a few inputs per second and react accordingly to them.
It does not have to save it, or produce an intuitive, logical reaction on the basis of previous maneuvers, so that it constantly takes only a handful of KB of memory.
There is no need for gigabyte- and megabyte-heavy memories.
This is the first step in the development of immediate collision avoidance technology, which, according to Nissan, will be serial in production within the next ten years.
Another application could find the technology in GPS satellite navigation by deliberately guiding the driver around obstacles and leading him to the goal.
